Vice President Kamala Harris spoke at the Chief of Mission Residence in Bangkok, Thailand, about the importance of addressing the climate crisis. She acknowledged the impact of the crisis on communities dependent on the Mekong River in Thailand, Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia, and Burma, including droughts, floods, extreme heat, and upstream development. Harris emphasized the need for all voices, including civil society, the private sector, and governments, to work together to develop solutions. She announced that the United States plans to provide up to $20 million in funding to the Japan-U.S.-Mekong Power Partnership to support clean energy transition and energy security in the Mekong region. Additionally, Harris mentioned support for the Mekong-Mississippi Sister Rivers partnership, which focuses on water resources management. She concluded by emphasizing the importance of collective action and the United States' commitment to supporting the economic development of the Mekong region and investing in a clean energy future.